# Repository Structure

**Project**: LLM Engineering in Practice

## Current philosophy (simple & incremental)

1. **Active learning code** lives under **`src/weekN/dayN/`** — one folder per day.
2. **Create subfolders only when needed** for that day (e.g. `prompts/`, `data/`, `eval/`, `rag/`, `agents/`). No empty placeholder trees.
3. **`src/setup/`** is the **only** shared exception — environment diagnostics and troubleshooting.
4. **`.backup/`** — frozen archive (full weekly guides, old notebooks, prompts, scripts). Restore or copy into the live tree **when** you need that material.
5. **`source-material/`** — read-only reference; **zero-copy** synthesis into `src/` (or `docs/`) when migrating ideas.

## `src/` layout (example)

```text
src/
├── README.md
├── setup/                 # diagnostics — not tied to a single day
└── week1/
    └── day1/              # today = only what Day 1 needs
        ├── README.md
        ├── day1.ipynb
        ├── scraper.py
        └── eval/
            └── log_utils.py
```

## Other repo folders

| Location | Purpose |
| -------- | ------- |
| `docs/` | Learning plan, setup notes, reports (lightweight); full `weeks/*.md` may live in `.backup/` until restored |
| `tools/` | Shell / PowerShell helpers (optional) |
| `.backup/` | Archived content — do not treat as the active working tree |
| `source-material/` | Read-only staging — never edit or delete |

## Prompts & eval (where they go)

- **Prefer** `src/weekN/dayN/prompts/` and `src/weekN/dayN/eval/` when that day introduces them.
- Avoid scattering root-level `prompts/`, `eval/`, `notebooks/` unless you deliberately choose a monorepo layout (legacy copies may sit in `.backup/`).

## Single source of truth for “what to do today”

- **Day scope:** `src/weekN/dayN/README.md`
- **Course roadmap:** `docs/learning-plan.md`
- **Deep weekly detail (if archived):** `.backup/docs/weeks/WeekN.md`
